<section id="fs-idm394790368">
<title>Introduction</title>
<para id="fs-idm388896448">As the Civil War was drawing to a close in the spring of 1865, there was debate about the terms the South would face upon its defeat. President Abraham Lincoln proposed a policy of reconstruction that sought to reunify the Union as smoothly and painlessly as possible, a theme evident in his second inaugural address in March 1865. This view was not universal, however; there were many among the “Radical” Republicans who were critical of Lincoln’s policy and felt the South should be punished for its act of treason. This political cartoon, drawn in 1865 by Joseph E. Baker, was a take on this controversy.</para>
<section id="fs-idm385136368">
